        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 40-year-old woman presents with a painless lesion on her ear lobe (shown in the image) after getting her ears pierced 3 months ago. Which of the following best explains the pathogenesis of this lesion?</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/06/picture1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"168\"></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7951746",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31738,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. D)</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Maturation arrest of collagen assembly</strong></span><br>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Keloid </strong>is a scar that tends to<strong> progress beyond the site of initial injury </strong>and <strong>recurs after excision</strong>. <strong>Dark-skinned persons </strong>are <strong>more frequently affected by keloids </strong>than light-skinned people. Keloids are characterized by <i><strong>changes in the ratio of type III to type I collagen</strong></i>, suggesting a <strong>“maturation arrest” </strong>in the healing process.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">This is the hallmark of <strong>keloid formation</strong>. In keloids, there is an <strong>overproduction of collagen type I </strong>which is unable to reorganise itself into a proper scar. This results in a<strong> thickened and raised scar </strong>that grows <strong>beyond the boundary of the original wound</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A.&nbsp;</strong>While<strong> extracellular matrix components</strong>, including <strong>proteoglycans, </strong>play a role in <strong>wound healing</strong>, their turnover is not the primary defect in keloid formation.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Granulation tissue </strong>is the<strong> new connective tissue and microscopic blood vessels </strong>that form on the <strong>surfaces of a wound during the healing process</strong>. <strong>Exuberant granulation tissue </strong>can lead to<strong> hypertrophic scars</strong>, which are <strong>similar to keloids </strong>but do not grow beyond the boundaries of the original wound.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C.&nbsp;</strong>This process is more related to the <strong>formation of granulation tissue </strong>during wound <strong>healing</strong>. Although it is an essential part of the healing process, it does not specifically lead to keloids.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>In keloids</strong>, there is an imbalance in the <strong>synthesis and degradation of collagen</strong>, with an <strong>increase in the ratio of type I to type III collagen</strong>. This suggests a<strong> failure </strong>in the normal <strong>maturation process </strong>of <strong>collagen during wound healing</strong>, leading to the<strong> excessive scar formation typical of keloids</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ref:</strong> https://journals.lww.com/prsgo/fulltext/2013/07000/keloids_and_hypertrophic_scars__update_and_future.5.aspx</span></p>",
