          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Overproduction of 1,25 dihydroxy vitamin D </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 56398,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Dystrophic calcification </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 56399,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Mutation in calcium sensing receptors </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 56400,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Increased reabsorption of calcium</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Nephrocalcinosis in a systemic granulomatous disease is due to: </span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4376629",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31742,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Overproduction of 1,25 dihydroxy vitamin D</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In <strong>chronic granulomatous inflammation, </strong>the important cells involved are <strong>macrophages and lymphocytes. </strong>There is presence of <strong>metastatic calcification due to activation </strong>of <strong>vitamin D precursor by macrophages</strong>&hellip;&hellip;.direct line from <strong>Robbins</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Macrophages in granulomas </strong>possess the enzyme<strong> 1-alpha-hydroxylase</strong>, which converts<strong> 25-hydroxyvitamin D </strong>to its active form, <strong>1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D</strong>. The unregulated production of this active form leads to <strong>increased intestinal absorption of calcium and phosphate</strong>, which can precipitate as <strong>calcium phosphate in the renal tubules</strong>, causing <strong>nephrocalcinosis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>&nbsp;Dystrophic calcification </strong>occurs in areas of <strong>necrosis or damage, </strong>irrespective of <strong>serum calcium levels</strong>. This type of calcification is<strong> not </strong>directly related to <strong>systemic granulomatous disease or vitamin D metabolism.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Mutations </strong>in<strong> calcium-sensing receptors (CaSR) </strong>can lead to alterations in <strong>calcium homeostasis</strong>. However, <strong>CaSR mutations </strong>typically cause disorders such as<strong> familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia, </strong>not nephrocalcinosis in the context of granulomatous disease.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">While <strong>increased reabsorption of calcium </strong>in the kidneys can contribute to <strong>hypercalcemia, </strong>it is not typically due to systemic <strong>granulomatous disease</strong>. It may occur as a <strong>secondary effect of hypercalcemia </strong>from other causes, such as<strong> primary hyperparathyroidism.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In<strong> systemic granulomatous diseases, </strong>the overproduction of the active form o<strong>f vitamin D by macrophages </strong>leads to <strong>increased calcium absorption </strong>and can result in <strong>nephrocalcinosis </strong>due to <strong>calcium deposition in the kidneys</strong>. </span></span></span></p>",
