      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 20-year-old man sustains a deep, open laceration over his left thigh in a motorcycle accident. The wound is cleaned and sutured. Which of the following cell types mediates contraction of the wound to facilitate healing?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4670343",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31737,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Myofibroblasts</span></strong></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>myofibroblast </strong>is the cell responsible for <strong>wound contraction as well as the deforming pathologic process </strong>termed <strong>wound contracture</strong>. These <strong>cells express a-smooth muscle actin, desmin, and vimentin, </strong>and they respond to <strong>pharmacologic agents </strong>that cause <strong>smooth muscle to contract or relax</strong>.&nbsp; The myofibroblasts exert their<strong> contractile </strong>effects by <strong>forming syncytia</strong>, in which the <strong>myofibroblasts are bound together by tight junctions. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">. <strong>Endothelial</strong> cells respond to <strong>growth factors and form capillaries, </strong>which are necessary for the delivery of <strong>nutrients and inflammatory cells</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Fibroblasts</strong> tend to be <strong>solitary cells, surrounded by collagen fibers</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">. <strong>Macrophages</strong> or <strong>smooth muscle cells </strong>mediate <strong>wound contraction</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:11.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Myofibroblasts </strong>are responsible for <strong>wound contraction, </strong>which helps reduce the size of the <strong>wound and is essential for wound healing.</strong></span></span></span></p>",
