      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Regeneration</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Superficial abrasions </strong>of the skin heal by a<strong> process of regeneration</strong>. It is mediated by <strong>stem cells or stabile cells </strong>that are able to progress through the <strong>cell cycle and fully restore normal tissue organization and function</strong>.<strong> Cellular migration </strong>is the predominant means by which the <strong>wound surface is reepithelialized. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Regeneration</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> refers to the <strong>replacement of lost tissue </strong>with tissue identical in <strong>structure and function </strong>to the original tissue. This is what occurs in superficial wounds, like<strong> abrasions</strong>, where the damage <strong>does not penetrate below the layer of basement membrane, </strong>and the wound can heal <strong>without </strong>the formation of significant <strong>scar tissue.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A.</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;Healing by <strong>secondary intention </strong>occurs when a<strong> wound is left open </strong>and<strong> closes naturally</strong> by the process of <strong>granulation tissue formation, contraction, and epithelialization. </strong>It is typical for<strong> deeper wounds, extensive damage, or when the edges cannot be brought together</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Granulation tissue</strong> is the <strong>new connective tissue and tiny blood vessels </strong>that form on the surface of a<strong> wound </strong>during the <strong>healing process</strong>. It typically occurs in <strong>deeper wounds </strong>that need to fill in with<strong> new tissue.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Healing by<strong> primary intention</strong> happens when the<strong> wound edges are brought together</strong>, as in a <strong>surgical incision or a clean cut</strong>. The edges are<strong> approximated </strong>and heal with<strong> minimal scar formation.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Superficial abrasions </strong>heal by <strong>regeneration </strong>because they involve only the<strong> epidermis or the upper dermis, </strong>which can <strong>fully restore </strong>the <strong>normal tissue organization and function</strong>. The process is mediated by the<strong> migration of epithelial cells to cover the wound surface. </strong></span></span></span></p>",
