        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Vitamin C</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) </strong>is a powerful, biologic reducing agent that is necessary for the<strong> hydroxylation of proline </strong>residues in collagen. Most of the clinical features associated with <strong>vitamin C deficiency (scurvy) </strong>are caused by the <strong>formation of an abnormal collagen </strong>that<strong> lacks tensile strength</strong>. Patients with vitamin C deficiency exhibit<strong> poor wound healing</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Vitamin C</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> is crucial for <strong>collagen synthesis</strong>. It acts as a <strong>cofactor for the enzymes prolyl hydroxylase and lysyl hydroxylase</strong>, which are necessary for the<strong> hydroxylation of proline and lysine</strong>. This step is critical for <strong>collagen molecules to form a stable structure </strong>that has the <strong>tensile strength required in scar tissue</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Folic</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>acid</strong> is crucial for <strong>DNA synthesis and repair, and cell division</strong>. It is particularly important in rapidly <strong>dividing tissues, </strong>like those in a<strong> healing wound</strong>, but it is not directly involved in collagen synthesis.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Thiamine</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> (Vitamin B1) is important in<strong> carbohydrate metabolism and energy production</strong>, but it does not play a direct role in collagen synthesis or wound healing.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Vitamin A</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> is involved in <strong>cell proliferation, immune function, and inflammatory response. </strong>It can help with <strong>wound healing </strong>and has been shown to<strong> reverse the inhibition of collagen synthesis </strong>that is caused by<strong> steroids</strong>. However, its role is not in the hydroxylation of proline residues in collagen.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Vitamin C </strong>is required for the<strong> hydroxylation of proline and lysine in collagen synthesis</strong>, making it <strong>essential for proper collagen assembly and wound healing</strong>.<strong> Deficiency in vitamin C leads to scurvy</strong>, characterized by<strong> poor wound healing and abnormal collagen with decreased tensile strength</strong>.</span></span></span></p>",
